Question 1

Letâs begin by fitting a model where wage_percent_of_male is the outcome variable and the explanatory variables are year and major_category. As we learned in our previous homework, we should always relevel categorical variables with more than one category in order to be sure what the model output is telling us. So letâs do that first. Letâs make âManagement, Business, and Financialâ the reference category. Our results will be in comparison to this group.

gender_employment <- gender_employment |>

Question 2

The model above assumes parallel trends. This means that we are telling the model to draw a line for each major category, and let the lines start at different points but make the slopes the same. The only thing that changes across major categories then is the intercept of the lines.

Letâs check if this assumption is warranted. Using the code from the introductory section, make a similar plot but facet it by major category so that lines vary across categories. What do you notice? Is the parallel trends assumption warranted?

ggplot(gender_employment, 
       mapping = aes(x = year, y = wage_percent_of_male)) +
   geom_jitter(alpha = .3) +
   geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + 
  labs(title = "Women's earnings with respect to men's", 
       y = "% of Men's Income", 
       x = "Year") +
    facet_wrap(~major_category)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
Warning: Removed 846 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_smooth()`).
Warning: Removed 846 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

The parallel trends assumption is not warranted because the slopes of each line by category are not parallel when we examine each separate relationship between wage percent of male and year. Some lines have positive slopes and trend up, while other categories have negative relationships with lines that trend down over time.

Question 4

Given that we have the ability to add interactions to models - i.e.Â to have slopes vary across categories -, why would we choose to build a model that assumes parallel trends?

When we choose to build a model that assumes parallel trends, we can directly compare which line is higher/lower than another because this type of model still allows for different intercepts but makes all lines have the same slope. This baseline look allows us to easily say that one category/line has a higher âdependent variableâ on average over âindependent variableâ than another category/line if it lies above this other line.

Before we build the model we want to explore the relationship between these variables. Like in the chapter, use select() and cor() to find the correlations between these three variables. Because we have some missing values, you want to give cor() the argument use = "complete.obs".

Describe the relationships between the variables.

The relationship between year and wage percent of male is a very weak positive linear correlation because 0.02 is very close to 0. Same with the relationship between year and percent female; a very weak positive relationship because the correlation coefficient is 0.005, very close to 0. However, there is a stronger positive linear relationship between wage percent of male and percent female because the correlation coefficient is 0.111, higher than the other coefficients.

What we want to to know, however, is the relationship between year and the paygap conditional on the proportion of women who work in an occupation. This is where the model described above comes handy. Build that model and save it as multiple_fit. Then, use tidy() to summarize the results. Describe the results in your own words. multiple_fit <- lm(wage_percent_of_male ~ year*percent_female, data = gender_employment)

The linear model for multiple_fit is = -800.111 + 0.438(year) + 10.637(percent_female) + (-0.005)(year)(percent_female). The higher percentage of women in the workforce for a give occupation, the lower the pay gap, or the higher the wage percent of males, in that occupation. This is because the slope of this line is positive overall, as shown by the graph below. Also, when examining how year fits into the results, we can also see that this pay gap decreases over time (as the years increase), shown by the slope for year of 0.438.

This is what I expected because it makes sense that when women are more represented in an occupation, they are paid closer to what the men are paid because they are likely to be performing similar jobs when there are a similar number of each sex.

Question 6

Here, we will practice some model comparison and I will also introduce you to another useful tool from the broom package.

First, letâs review the discussion about R squared. Briefly tell me, in your own words, what R squared is.

R squared is the "coefficient of determination" that describes how much of the variation dependent variable is explain by the linear model relating this dependent variable to an explanatory variable. The closer to 0 r-squared is, the less of the variation in y that the model explains. The closer to 1 r-squared is, the more of the variation in y that the model explains.

Okay, letâs now compare the R squared for simple_fit and multiple_fit. To do this we are going to use glance() from the broom package. Run glance() on simple_fit. This should give you a lot of information, including the R squared. It turns out that you can save that output doing something like this.

And then you can access the R squared, the same way you would access a column from a dataframe, with the $ sign.

Do this for both models and compare the R squared. What can you conclude from this?

simple_glanced <- glance(simple_fit)

simple_glanced$r.squared
[1] 0.0005778711
multiple_glanced <- glance(multiple_fit)

multiple_glanced$r.squared
[1] 0.01321338

The r-squared value for the simple fit model is 0.0005778711.

The r-squared value for the multiple fit model is 0.01321338.

Although they are both very low and close to 0, the multiple fit model has a higher r-squared value which means that this model explains more of the variation in the wage percent of male than the simple fit model. When we include the percent_female in the multiple fit model, the model can tell us more about what we need to know about the predicted wage percent of male considering the given year than if we omitted this additional explanatory variable like in the simple fit model.

WARNING SIGN

Now, I want to tell you a cautionary tale about R squared. While a useful metric, R squared has one big weakness: it improves when you add any variable to your model, regardless of how nonsensical it is. This is because R squared just takes into account the amount of variance explained and even random noise will be able to account for some variation. Letâs see this in action. I am going to create a vector of random values the same size as our dataframe.

random_numbers <- rnorm(n = nrow(gender_employment), 
                        mean = 0, 
                        sd = 4)

Now, I will add this column and put it into our model:

gender_employment$random_noise <- random_numbers

# New model 
random_fit <- lm(wage_percent_of_male ~ year + percent_female + random_noise, data = gender_employment)

Examine the R squared for yourself and consider the implications of this little exercise!

random_glanced <- glance(random_fit)

random_glanced$r.squared
[1] 0.01299465

The r-squared value for the random_fit model with the random noise added is 0.02252792. This is higher than if the random noise were to be omitted: 0.01297574, as shown below. Despite this additional data being meaningless with no practical implications, it made the model more âaccurateâ but accounting for more of the variation in the wage percent of male. Therefore, we must be very careful about what data we are using and how this data affects our procedures when making practical inferences about the real world from the results.

warning_fit <- lm(wage_percent_of_male ~ year + percent_female, data = gender_employment)

warning_glanced <- glance(warning_fit)

warning_glanced$r.squared
[1] 0.01297574
